# Responsive Images

Images are the heaviest assets on most pages. Making them responsive involves two concerns: **visual** (images must not overflow their container) and **performance** (mobile devices should not download desktop-sized images).

## Visual Responsiveness

One line of CSS makes all images visually responsive:

```css
img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; }
```

- `max-width: 100%` — the image cannot be wider than its container
- `height: auto` — maintains the original aspect ratio

## The srcset Attribute

`srcset` lets you provide multiple image files for different screen resolutions — the browser picks the best one:

```html
<img
  src="photo-800.jpg"
  srcset="photo-400.jpg 400w, photo-800.jpg 800w, photo-1200.jpg 1200w"
  sizes="(max-width: 480px) 100vw, (max-width: 768px) 50vw, 33vw"
  alt="Coding workspace">
```

## CSS Custom Properties (Variables)

CSS variables store values you reuse throughout a stylesheet. They start with `--`:

```css
:root {
  --color-primary:   #22c55e;
  --color-text:      #1e293b;
  --color-bg:        #f8fafc;
  --radius:          8px;
  --spacing-md:      16px;
  --spacing-lg:      32px;
}

.button {
  background: var(--color-primary);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  padding: var(--spacing-md);
}
```

Change `--color-primary` in one place and every element that uses `var(--color-primary)` updates instantly.

## Practical Responsive Patterns

**Fluid typography with clamp():**
```css
h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 5vw, 48px); }
```
Fluid between 24px (minimum) and 48px (maximum). `5vw` is the preferred size between.

**Responsive padding:**
```css
.section { padding: clamp(24px, 5vw, 80px) clamp(16px, 4vw, 120px); }
```

**Hiding elements at breakpoints:**
```css
.desktop-only { display: none; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) { .desktop-only { display: block; } }

.mobile-only {}
@media (min-width: 1024px) { .mobile-only { display: none; } }
```

